He...
text:
Once, when there had been only half as many heads, Gendry had caught Arya looking at them. “Admiring your work?” he asked.
He was angry because he’d liked Lucan, she knew, but it still wasn’t fair. “It’s Steelshanks Walton’s work,” she said defensively. “And the Mummers, and Lord Bolton.”
“And who gave us all them? You and your weasel soup.”
Arya punched his arm. “It was just hot broth. You hated Ser Amory too.”
“I hate this lot worse. Ser Amory was fighting for his lord, but the Mummers are sellswords and turncloaks. Half of them can’t even speak the Common Tongue. Septon Utt likes little boys, Qyburn does black magic, and your friend Biter eats people.”
The worst thing was, she couldn’t even say he was wrong.

summary: For the @asoiafrarepairs prompt: Day/Night By day, they are the perfect Stark siblings - Jon with the steel winter crown upon...
body:
For the @asoiafrarepairs prompt: Day/Night

By day, they are the perfect Stark siblings - Jon with the steel winter crown upon his head and Arya in her plain grey clothes - their heads always bent together, shadows so intertwined with one another than one can no longer tell where one begins and the other ends.

The sight of them bolsters the men at camp. They listen to Jon deliver his speeches and watch Arya pick apart at their defenses only for her to build them up again, stronger and more indestructible than ever, and thinks to themselves, Perhaps we might survive this yet. 

Because oh, how their enemies would tremble, to see the might of the North manifested in these two. They who are the last of Ned Stark’s blood, they who had seen what war did to children, they who had lost much and suffered much - they alone are worth an army. 

Together, they would give their people peace. But not before Northern justice has been served and the whole world has been brought to their knees. Not before they’ve defeated the Night King and pushed the darkness out of their lands. 

It is them against the world, the way it has always been.

But by night, it is a different story. They are each other’s worst enemies. They circle each other like wolves, drawn together by the red string of fate yet forever oceans apart, their minds at war with one another.

Jon longs to touch her, this creature who is both his sister and his cousin. He longs to trace the veins on her forearms, to mark her skin with kisses the way he’d done when they were but summer children, to show her he loves her in all the ways that he can.

And because he knows her so well, he can tell that Arya wants him too. Has known it from the first time she crawled into his bed, begging Jon with sleepy eyes to hold her until she falls asleep to keep the nightmares at bay. But he can’t. Even when she comes to him, throat bared and claws retracted, he cannot bring himself to touch her, however much his hand trembles so.

For what is a king without his honour? How could he ever live with himself, if he manages to drag his sweet sister into sin only to damn them both to hell by the strength of their own desires?

No, that is no way for Arya to live. The world has already taken so much from her. She deserves a man who can love her not just in secret, but in plain sight of the gods, both old and new. She deserves a man worthy of the love their father gave them. She deserves a crown of her own, and not one that is tainted by shame.

So Jon knows it can never be him. He could sin enough for the both of them, but by the gods, he will not touch his sister.


When the war is over, when all the dragons are dead and the blue-eyed armies have turned to ash, Arya comes to him in the dead of night, a half-starved wolf child come to check on her pack.

She looks at Jon in all his wounded glory and kisses him, and just like that, Jon breaks.

That night, they tear each other apart like soft-skinned wolves - hearts trembling, ribs wide open - and build themselves a castle filled with all the things left unsaid.

Jon buries his face in the crook of her shoulder, in home, and prays, Lord Stark, forgive me.
